'''''Legacy of the Force: Bloodlines''''' is the second novel in the ''[[Star Wars: Legacy of the Force]]'' series. Written by [[Karen Traviss]], it was released in the [[Wikipedia:United States|United States]] by [[Del Rey]] on [[August 29]] and in the [[Wikipedia:United Kingdom|U.K.]], [[Wikipedia:Australia|Australia]], and [[Wikipedia:New Zealand|New Zealand]] by [[Arrow Books|Arrow Publishing]] on [[September 7]], [[2006]]. ''Bloodlines'' contains a 20-page excerpt of the next book in the series, ''[[Legacy of the Force: Tempest]]'', by [[Troy Denning]]. The [[Legacy of the Force: Bloodlines (abridged audiobook)|audio version]] was narrated by [[Marc Thompson]]. The cover features [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]].

==Publisher's summary==
'''A new era of exciting adventures and shocking revelations continues to unfold, as the legendary ''Star Wars'' saga sweeps forward into astonishing new territory.'''

''Civil war looms as the fledgling Galactic Alliance confronts a growing number of rebellious worlds-and the approaching war is tearing the Skywalker and Solo families apart. Han and Leia return to Han's homeworld, Corellia, the heart of the resistance. Their children, Jacen and Jaina, are soldiers in the Galactic Alliance's campaign to crush the insurgents.''

''Jacen, now a complete master of the Force, has his own plans to bring order to the galaxy. Guided by his Sith mentor, Lumiya, and with Luke's young son Ben at his side, Jacen embarks on the same path that his grandfather Darth Vader once did. And while Han and Leia watch their only son become a stranger, a secret assassin entangles the couple with a dreaded name from Han's past: Boba Fett. In the new galactic order, friends and enemies are no longer what they seem.&hellip;''

==Plot summary==
After so many [[Standard decade/Legends|decades]] of close calls in his dangerous career as a [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]], it is [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett's]] [[Cloning/Legends|clone]] origins that may finally [[Death/Legends|kill]] him. Ten [[Standard year/Legends|years]] after the end of the [[Yuuzhan Vong War]], a [[Doctor/Legends|doctor]] diagnoses Fett with a defect in his [[Gene/Legends|genes]] that will give him at most a year to live. Fett begins a search for any clues that may unlock genetic secrets that will prolong his life. The tensions between the [[Galactic Federation of Free Alliances|Galactic Alliance]] and [[Corellia/Legends|Corellia]] have put [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] on edge as Corellia rallies support from independent-minded [[Planet/Legends|worlds]] that believe the Alliance is overstepping its bounds. [[Darth Caedus|Jacen]] thinks a stronger hand is needed to maintain order, but [[Chief of State (Galactic Alliance)|Chief of State]] [[Cal Omas]] disagrees. Jacen strikes up an alliance with the hawkish [[Admiral/Legends|Admiral]] [[Cha Niathal]] to push an agenda beyond Omas' reservations.

[[Han Solo/Legends|Han]] and [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia]] continue their rogue and incognito operations on Corellia, attempting to subvert the more provocative actions taken by the Alliance. Despite their efforts, [[Thrackan Sal-Solo]] still views them as the enemy. Sal-Solo, hardly a [[Politics/Legends|political]] idealist, sees the conflict as an opportunity to accrue more power and influence. Sal-Solo still intends to reactivate the [[Centerpoint Station]]. He enlists a number of black-op teams to target Han, Leia, and their children for assassination. Among Sal-Solo's hired guns is the [[Mercenary/Legends|mercenary]] Ailyn Habuur – who is actually Boba Fett's estranged daughter [[Ailyn Vel]]. [[Goran Beviin]], one of Boba Fett's close [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] confidants, brings him word that Fett's daughter has taken up the contract on the [[Solo family/Legends|Solos]]. With his time running out, Fett hopes to make amends with Ailyn. A young [[Gender/Legends|female]] Mandalorian bounty hunter named [[Mirta Gev]] finds Fett and offers to help him track Ailyn down, promising information that can help. 

[[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] is troubled by the conflict that has befallen the Galactic Alliance after actions he believes to be just. Furthermore, he is plagued by recurring [[Force vision/Legends|visions]] of a mysterious [[Dark side of the Force/Legends|dark]] man who threatens [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]]. Luke senses a darkness on Coruscant, but he cannot identify the source. Though Luke has reservations about [[Ben Skywalker|Ben's]] attachment to Jacen – and his obvious hero worship – Mara thinks Jacen is a good influence. With each success against the enemy, Jacen gains more authority from the Alliance. He is offered command of the [[Galactic Alliance Guard]] (GAG), a [[Law enforcement agency/Legends|secret police force]] meant to ensure security. [[Supreme Commander (Alliance)/Legends|Supreme Commander]] [[Gilad Pellaeon/Legends|Gilad Pellaeon]] steps down from his position, citing differences with the direction the Alliance is heading. Admiral Niathal assumes Pellaeon's command, extending Jacen's influence over the military.

It is not an easy mantle Jacen wears, but he is buoyed by the public support for his actions. Jacen is increasingly convinced that the dark side is not evil – in the hands of the right person, it's the necessary application of force and action – sentiments once spoused by [[Vergere]]. For reassurance, Jacen [[Flow-walking|flow-walks]], a [[Space-time continuum/Legends|time-twisting]] [[Force power/Legends|Force ability]] that allows him to experience past events firsthand, to witness the actions of his [[Parent/Legends|grandfather]], [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]], during the rise of the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Empire]]. Jacen sees [[Operation: Knightfall/Legends|Anakin's assault on the Jedi Temple]] and judges his grandfather to have been misguided; Anakin simply was not strong enough to resist the destructive power of the dark side. Jacen believes he can do better. Under his command, the Alliance escalates the tense [[Blockade/Legends|blockade]] around Corellia, pushing the conflict into open war. Jacen has Ben serve in the GAG. One of Jacen's first orders is imprisoning the [[Corellian/Legends|Corellians]] on Coruscant to defend against [[Terrorist/Legends|terrorist]] strikes that have threated peace on the capital. In rounding up suspects, the Guard arrests Ailyn Vel. Jacen brutally [[Torture/Legends|interrogates]] her using [[The Force/Legends|the Force]], killing Ailyn in the process.

[[Dur Gejjen]], the political rival of Thrackan Sal-Solo, wants the dangerous Corellian eliminated and proposes that Han eliminate his cousin. Fett also approaches Han, wanting to use him as bait to lure Ailyn Vel. In return, Fett will kill Sal-Solo for Han. Donning [[Mandalorian armor/Legends|Mandalorian armor]], Han accompanies Mirta and Fett as trey track down Sal-Solo. Mirta kills the Corellian [[Head of State/Legends|Head of State]]. Han discovers that Ailyn was a [[Prisoner/Legends|captive]] of the GAG and died in [[Prison/Legends|custody]], though he remains unaware that Jacen is to blame. Contacting Jacen, Han arranges for Ailyn's body to be delivered to [[Mandalore/Legends|Mandalore]] for a proper [[Funeral/Legends|burial]]. In a surprising turn, Fett discovers that Mirta is in truth Ailyn's daughter, and therefore his granddaughter.

During an assault on Corellian forces, [[Jaina Solo Fel|Jaina]] refuses a direct order from Jacen to destroy a defenseless target. For punishment, Jacen removes her from duty. His hard line stance and ruthless actions further distance him from his family. Ben is the sole exception; he continues to admire his cousin's decisive victories, shielded from the more gruesome truths behind them. [[Lumiya]], who still guides Jacen through the ways of the [[Sith/Legends|Sith]], tells him this is but the start. Turning against his loved ones is a process that demands sacrifice. Jacen is chilled to realize that sacrifice may one day demand the deaths of [[Tenel Ka Djo|Tenel Ka]] and his daughter, [[Allana Djo Solo|Allana]]. When Fett learns from Beviin that Jacen Solo was in fact responsible for the death of Ailyn, he does not spring into action. Fett decides watching the Solo family disintegrate from within is suitable revenge.

==Development==
The working title for ''Bloodlines'' was ''Necessary Evil''. Like [[Karen Traviss]]' other ''[[Star Wars]]'' novels, it heavily features the [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorian]] culture she helped develop for the ''[[Republic Commando]]'' series.<ref name="TERC" />

The [[Science Fiction Book Club]] released an exclusive hardcover version of this novel.<ref name="SFBC">{{SFBC|url=doc/full_site_enrollment/detail/fse_product_detail.jhtml?repositoryId=497056B510|text=Star Wars: Legacy of the Force: Bloodlines}}</ref>

==Continuity==
Even for many avid ''[[Star Wars]]'' readers of novels and comics, the appearance of [[Ailyn Vel|Boba Fett's daughter]] came as a surprise. She originated in a single story in ''[[Star Wars Tales]]'', an anthology series that sometimes overtly separated itself form the established expectations of continuity, both retrospectively and prospectively, to allow the talents at [[Dark Horse Comics]] leeway to tell a lively mix of stories. [[Star Wars Tales 7|Issue #7]], published in [[2001]], carried the story of "[[Outbid But Never Outgunned]]" written by [[Beau Smith]] and artists [[Mike Deodato, Jr.]] and [[Neil Nelson]]. The sixteen page tale had [[Boba Fett/Legends|Boba Fett]] and [[Sintas Vel]] both chasing down a [[Holorecorder/Legends|holographic recording]] that was being auctioned off by a [[Gangster/Legends|mobster]]. The recording shows Fett and Vel standing together as husband and wife, holding their infant daughter.<ref name="TERC" />

Though this story could have been chalked up as noncontinuity, Sintas and her daughter were later referenced in "[[Unusual Suspects]]," an article by [[Andrew Hind]] that appeared in ''[[Star Wars Gamer 6]]'' (2001), and "[[The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors|The History of the Mandalorians]]," an article by [[Abel G. Peña]] in [[Star Wars Insider 80|''Star Wars Insider'' #80]] ([[2005]]). Their mention in ''Bloodlines'' was their first appearance within a prose story, as well as the first appearance of the next generation in Fett's family, [[Mirta Gev]] (who was originally named Vessin Ghif in the outline).<ref name="TERC" />

